description:
Yet another meme related soundcloud experiment.
Explanation below:








The waveform soundcloud generated lies to you about this sound's true nature. Why does it do this?

When soundcloud renders a waveform for a song, it scrolls through the song and periodically records the volume of it. It then forms these volumes into a series of bars and displays that as the sound's waveform.

While normally this will produce the intended behavior, it can also be exploited to create abominations like this.

Zoomed in, the ACTUAL waveform of this sound is a series of very short pulses (0.1 ms) separated by comparatively long amounts of 'silence' (5ms). AS A RESULT, when soundcloud tries to sample this sound, it will more often than not end up sampling the 'silence' rather than the pulses. This is why the waveform looks the way it does.

Why isn't is perfectly silent? For the most part, the answer is lossy mp3 compression. The 'silence' was actually turned into a quiet white noise when soundcloud converted the upload to an mp3 file.
title: Loud?
